<body>
  <h1>Bhai Mati Das Ji</h1>
  <h2>The Exemplary Sikh Martyr</h2>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>Early Life</h2>
    <p>
      Bhai Mati Das Ji was born in the mid-17th century in a devout Sikh family
      in Punjab. He was the elder brother of Bhai Sati Das Ji and grew up under
      the spiritual guidance of his father, Bhai Hira Nand, a respected Sikh.
      His early life was marked by a deep commitment to Sikh principles and
      service.
    </p>
    <div class="media-container">
      <div class="media-item">
        <img src="/media/matiDas.jpg" alt="Bhai Mati Das Young" />
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>Family Life</h2>
    <p>
      Bhai Mati Das Ji was married and had a family, including his brother Bhai
      Sati Das. His household was a center of Sikh values, where he instilled
      courage and devotion in his loved ones. His wife and family supported his
      mission alongside Guru Tegh Bahadur Ji.
    </p>
    <div class="media-container">
      <div class="media-item">
        <img src="/media/matiDas.jpg" alt="Bhai Mati Das Family" />
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>Contributions to Sikhi</h2>
    <p>
      Bhai Mati Das Ji was a skilled preacher and a close companion of Guru Tegh
      Bahadur Ji. He played a key role in spreading Sikh teachings, emphasizing
      equality, justice, and devotion. His efforts strengthened the Sikh
      community during challenging times under Mughal rule.
    </p>
    <div class="media-container">
      <div class="media-item">
        <video controls>
          <source src="/media/video.mp4" type="video/mp4" />
          Your browser does not support the video tag.
        </video>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>Martyrdom</h2>
    <p>
      In 1675, Bhai Mati Das Ji was arrested with Guru Tegh Bahadur Ji in Delhi.
      Refusing to convert to Islam, he was brutally sawed alive in public. His
      martyrdom on November 24, 1675, inspired countless Sikhs and remains a
      symbol of ultimate sacrifice for faith.
    </p>
    <div class="media-container">
      <div class="media-item">
        <img src="/media/matiDas.jpg" alt="Bhai Mati Das Martyrdom" />
      </div>
      <div class="media-item">
        <video controls>
          <source src="/media/video.mp4" type="video/mp4" />
          Your browser does not support the video tag.
        </video>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>Legacy</h2>
    <p>
      Bhai Mati Das Ji's life and death continue to inspire Sikhs worldwide. His
      courage is commemorated in Sikh history and Gurbani. Listen to a
      recitation in his honor:
    </p>
    <div class="media-container">
      <div class="media-item">
        <audio controls>
          <source src="/media/audio.mp3" type="audio/mp3" />
          Your browser does not support the audio element.
        </audio>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</body>
